## 2026-01-12 - Initial Creation

**RED Phase Documentation:**
- **Gap identified**: When working with Windows security analysis, malware reverse engineering, or capability development, Claude needs authoritative reference material on advanced Windows system mechanisms, virtualization technologies, management/diagnostics, caching/file systems, and boot processes
- **Test scenario**: "Explain how Windows VBS (Virtualization-Based Security) and Virtual Secure Mode work, including the Secure Kernel and VTL isolation"
- **Without skill**: Claude would provide general information from training data, potentially missing implementation details, architectural specifics, or getting technical details incorrect
- **With skill**: Claude can reference the authoritative Windows Internals 7th Edition Part 2 book, providing accurate, detailed technical information directly from Microsoft kernel engineers

**Skill Details:**
- **Name**: windows-internals-part2
- **Location**: .claude/skill-library/security/windows/windows-internals-part2/
- **Category**: Library skill (security/windows)
- **Type**: Library/Framework (reference documentation)
- **Source**: Windows Internals 7th Edition Part 2 by Allievi, Ionescu, Russinovich, Solomon (2022)
- **Book location**: Books/Winternals7thPt2_full_repair.md (27,497 lines)

**Coverage:**
- Chapter 8: System mechanisms (side-channel mitigations, traps, interrupts, exceptions, system calls, WoW64, Object Manager, synchronization, ALPC, WNF)
- Chapter 9: Virtualization technologies (Hyper-V, VBS, VSM, VTLs, Secure Kernel, HVCI, IUM, enclaves)
- Chapter 10: Management, diagnostics, and tracing (registry, services, Task Scheduler, WMI, ETW, DTrace, WER, shims)
- Chapter 11: Caching and file systems (Cache Manager, NTFS, ReFS, filter drivers)
- Chapter 12: Startup and shutdown (UEFI, Secure Boot, boot process, kernel initialization)

